column9:

Hi there,

To optimize cloud resources, we automatically pause free-tier projects after 7 days of inactivity.

Your project Monthly reports (https://supabase.com/dashboard/project/vyuxyyfxbefdjrgtglkj) has been paused.

You can unpause your project from the dashboard within 90 days. After this period, the project cannot be restored, but your data will remain available for download. View documentation for details: https://supabase.com/docs/guides/platform/migrating-and-upgrading-projects#time-limits

To prevent future automatic pausing, upgrade to Pro from your billing settings: https://supabase.com/dashboard/org/_/billing?panel=subscriptionPlan

Have questions? Submit a support ticket (https://supabase.help) and our team will help.


Happy Hacking!


Ant

column7: Want an excuse to read more books? Use these templates:
column9:
‚Äã

Hey there!

A new template pack is now LIVE on Typeshare!

‚Äã

******************
Fiction As Content
******************

Every writer (and creator) should actively study literature.

Even if you don't plan on writing novels, "the greats" can teach
you exponentially more about language than any blogger or social
media writer can.

But unfortunately, reading rates of novels and short stories are
declining around the world. So, this holiday season, I want to
help turn your fiction reading into content so you can share your
favorite stories and inspire your audience to read more.

(
https://click.convertkit-mail2.
)‚Äã
That‚Äôs why I created the ‚ÄúFiction As Content‚Äù template pack.

Here are the templates you get inside:

* Must-Read Stories. Share 3 stories (novels, short stories,
etc.) that have changed the way you think about a topic and why
they‚Äôre better than any other ‚Äúregular‚Äù resource you might read
about it.
* Fiction Is My Secret Weapon. Explain how reading literature,
stories, plays, etc. has changed your professional or personal
life and which titles you recommend people start with first.#
* Start With These Stories. Recommend the best works of fiction
in a particular genre that will a) help your audience develop in
their industry or niche and b) get more pleasure from reading.

*****************************************************************
However, these weekly template packs are only available to
Typeshare Pro Writers or Creators.

column7: ‚ÄúThe First Data Hire‚Äù Series: How to Survive and Succeed as a Solo Data Leader
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/the-first-data-hire-series-how-to

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here üëã
I‚Äôve had a few conversations with data experts who just started a new role as a data leader or are the first data hire. This is always a challenging situation as you‚Äôve got to set expectations and have to develop much of the infrastructure yourself. So I wanted to write an article series about being the first data hire.
But before that, if you're a data leader looking to understand what is going on in the broader data world as well as elevate your leadership skills, consider signing up for my 6-Week Data Leaders Playbook Accelerator program [ https://substack.com/redirect/1f1784bf-0794-4bda-aa4b-c16b9b8b757e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] that I will be running in September!
Now, let‚Äôs jump into the article!
Being the first data hire is one of the most common (and chaotic) experiences I hear about from data engineers and analysts.
Sometimes you‚Äôre the first hire for the entire company. Other times, you‚Äôre brought in to support a single department. Either way, the situation tends to feel the same: exciting, overwhelming, and a little bit absurd.
On one hand, you have a blank slate. You get to build what you think matters. On the other, there‚Äôs no process, no standards, and everyone wants something from you, yesterday.
Leadership might assume you‚Äôll wave a magic wand and spin up the same infrastructure they had at their last company, where a 20-person team shipped real-time dashboards and full-blown applications already integrated with AI and delivering insights.
Meanwhile, you‚Äôre one person staring down 30 semi-automated workflows cobbled together in Google Sheets, Access, and a random script Terry developed back in 2018. Plus a backlog of 100+ requests from people who don‚Äôt know what they want, only that they want it now.
So, where do you start?
That‚Äôs what this article is about. Whether you're new to the role or just walked into another "first hire‚Äù situation, I‚Äôll walk through the most common mistakes, the frameworks I‚Äôve seen work, and how to prioritize projects when everyone‚Äôs asking for everything.
SeattleDataGuy‚Äôs Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Mistakes New Data Leaders Make
Before we get into what to do, let‚Äôs talk about what not to do. These are some of the most common mistakes I see new data leaders make. I‚Äôm sure there are more, if you‚Äôve experienced this, feel free to share your own below so others can learn from them, too.
Trying to Solve Every Problem for Every Leader at Once
One of the biggest traps early on is trying to please everyone. I recently spoke with a data leader about how to juggle requests from half a dozen stakeholders [ https://substack.com/redirect/953d7059-ef95-42ca-a0f7-99890cf2b1e8?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] with no clear priorities and nowhere near enough bandwidth.
Sure, hiring more help is ideal. But realistically, you‚Äôll hit a point where you have to make tough calls. You can‚Äôt solve every problem. And more importantly, you shouldn‚Äôt have to. You need to communicate who you can and can‚Äôt support. What will and won‚Äôt be done. Just because you can try to track a dozen levers and metrics doesn‚Äôt mean you should. The challenge here is, when you‚Äôre the new data leader, people will come to you. They will have long lists, they will try to find ways to become a priority, whether what they want aligns with the business goals or not. I can promise you, it will be overwhelming all while you‚Äôre trying to wrap your head around the companies data infrastructure [ https://substack.com/redirect/82b76f82-2912-4148-816d-4ce5c0e9fb1c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. 
When you‚Äôre first getting started, focus on discovery. Interview key stakeholders, learn their goals, and figure out which ones align with broader business objectives and have an interest in partnering with you.
>From there, build a simple prioritization matrix to help you decide where to focus your time and who you‚Äôre realistically able to help.
Neglecting to Build Relationships
No matter who you end up supporting, building strong relationships across the business is non-negotiable.
It‚Äôs tempting to hunker down and focus on delivering dashboards or machine learning models [ https://substack.com/redirect/7f41f13a-0f2f-4db1-ab00-a59594652c0a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. But shipping alone isn‚Äôt enough, those tools still need to be used, integrated, and maintained. If you‚Äôre building a dashboard, who‚Äôs going to embed it into the workflow? Do they even know you‚Äôre working on it?
Beyond implementation, relationships help surface better problems to solve. When you‚Äôre regularly talking with stakeholders, outside of just gathering requirements, you‚Äôll start to hear the real challenges they‚Äôre facing. The ones they may not mention in a formal request. That‚Äôs where some of your most valuable, creative work can come from.
Focus Purely on Tooling
I‚Äôve said this before, but it‚Äôs worth repeating: building infra for the sake of infra is a great way to never deliver anything the business needs [ https://substack.com/redirect/3ddef29f-e489-4c88-80de-a45e908dbba3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. It‚Äôs also a great way to lose trust.
I‚Äôve seen teams go all-in on the ‚Äúperfect‚Äù architecture or the latest tool, only to emerge weeks later with a solution no one asked for. Or worse, a dashboard with numbers the business doesn‚Äôt trust.
If you don‚Äôt bring stakeholders along for the ride, don‚Äôt be surprised when they question the output. Technical elegance doesn‚Äôt matter if the business can‚Äôt use (or believe in) what you‚Äôve built.
Guiding Principles for a Startup Data Strategy
Now that we‚Äôve covered what not to do, let‚Äôs talk about principles you can use to better approach building your data infrastructure.
Also, if you‚Äôd like, I recently ran a live webinar discussing this very topic!
Start Simple, Focus on Value
It sounds obvious, but it‚Äôs easy to forget: most businesses don‚Äôt need the perfect infrastructure, they need answers.
I‚Äôve seen too many teams chase perfection when all the business needed was a handful of reliable metrics. 
I mean, the amount of times a pivot table would have answered more questions that the overly complex dashboard the data team did end up developing‚Ä¶
In many cases, you can get by with something as simple as a replica of your database and run your analytics from there, and that‚Äôs more than fine to start with.
Hype is not a data strategy. [ https://substack.com/redirect/7796e08c-9007-4100-af69-a737d3f65148?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Balance Speed and Scalability
If you‚Äôre the first data hire, the business will likely have:
A lot of requests
No process for how to actually use data
So your job early on isn‚Äôt to build a full-blown data warehouse [ https://substack.com/redirect/65947ef1-acff-42dc-ae43-374aa551713c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. It‚Äôs to find simple, practical ways to use data to move the business forward.
Start by delivering a few key reports or even just a light analysis that give insights into things the company can‚Äôt currently see or can‚Äôt answer. For example:
Churn is higher than expected - Can you answer why and which segments are actually churning or at the highest risk to?
Customer acquisition costs are trending up - figure out if certain channels are underperforming or if marketing spend isn‚Äôt aligned with high-LTV [ https://substack.com/redirect/b7978cb0-c4fb-4792-a09f-f3c2cf1a602f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] customers, and suggest reallocations.
Inventory levels are inconsistent across systems - trace how data flows from suppliers to warehouse and POS, identify where mismatches occur, and work with operations to fix broken processes or integrations.
That way the business gets familiar with using data and you get familiar with the data that represents the business.
Trust and quality > quantity
There are a lot of conversations around the speed of development for data team [ https://substack.com/redirect/99587289-a148-4f3c-9843-a2733aee5c73?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Yes, leadership wants insights fast, but constantly churning out dashboards with bad or inconsistent data is a quick way to lose trust.
Whether you‚Äôre generating AI SQL slop or just turning your data team into a dashboard factory.
The more dashboards and data products you create, the more likely it is that things won‚Äôt reconcile. So even if the business is asking for 100 dashboards, take a step back and consider the following:
A 1,000-person company probably doesn‚Äôt need 100 dashboards
Multiple dashboards tracking the same metric with slight differences only create confusion
Every dashboard you build adds to your maintenance and overhead
It‚Äôs easy to fall into the ‚Äúmore is better‚Äù mindset when you‚Äôre the first data hire. I know that was me! But more can mean distraction, inconsistency, and a never-ending cycle of upkeep. 
Finding The Right Projects
Finding meaningful projects starts with a deep understanding of the business [ https://substack.com/redirect/0765b0c1-12f0-457d-a5da-4f96aa2a23c1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. As data engineers and analysts, we have unique access to core metrics [ https://substack.com/redirect/a4ff6b8e-ac96-4b49-9aa9-647dd84c2f7f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and raw data, giving us the tools to ask better questions and uncover insights others might miss.
The key is taking a moment to pause and reflect, rather than defaulting to shipping pipelines and dashboards. Ask questions about the data and how it connects to business outcomes.
For instance, if you work at a Starbucks, McDonald‚Äôs, or a Cava-type restaurant, a core metric might be comparable store sale [ https://substack.com/redirect/3009a937-b0d8-4c13-a0c0-e50a9754f9b9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]s. In a hotel, it‚Äôs probably Occupancy and average daily rate. But knowing the metrics isn‚Äôt enough, you need to understand what moves it.
Ask yourself:
What factors actually impact occupancy?
Was there a clear reason it dropped this week, like seasonality, a storm, or a local event?
Are competitors pricing lower?
If we reduced prices, would we see an increase?
If you‚Äôre still trying to figure out how to find the right projects, I‚Äôve written a near chapter‚Äôs worth of content here [ https://substack.com/redirect/122d9f24-65a6-418e-b119-9e6b93d9569e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Getting Buy-In
During your first month(or in some cases just the first few weeks), you‚Äôll probably get a bit of grace. People expect you to ramp up, learn the business, and identify gaps and opportunities. But soon enough, you‚Äôll need to start delivering value, and that means getting buy-in for projects.
Congrats‚Ä¶you‚Äôre in sales [ https://substack.com/redirect/420f8125-ac4c-4969-81c9-07e8246313e7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]!
Wes Kao  said it well in her interview with Lenny Rachitsky  : a lot of us get so caught up in logistics, we forget to focus on the sales.
The Abstract Is Hard: You‚Äôve heard ‚Äúshow, don‚Äôt tell.‚Äù Even if you can clearly explain your project, it helps a lot to show a tangible mock-up. Visuals reduce ambiguity and make your work easier to rally behind. I enjoyed the way Shachar Meir [ https://substack.com/redirect/b581df88-0a1a-4019-9209-87979fd98db9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] put it describing 1-hour, 1-day, or 1-month versions. If you can build an initial version of something in an hour so people can see it and understand the value you can get far more buy-in.
Anchor to Pain Points: People buy into solutions when they clearly solve something painful. I know, we all have the same inclination to lead with WHAT and HOW we‚Äôll be using to solve the problem instead of WHY it even matters. Sadly this requires us to have some empathy and understand, well, other people and their needs. Instead of ‚ÄúWe should build a churn dashboard,‚Äù try: ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre losing 15% of customers each quarter, here‚Äôs a quick analysis on why.‚Äù Now the value of a deeper project is obvious.
Enlist Champions: Find someone influential who feels the pain your project solves. If they‚Äôre excited, they can help champion the idea internally and build momentum with peers or leadership. I know it can be tempting to try to solve every problem on your own. But the world, fun fact, does not revolve around you and other people would love to help(as long as you can show them why they also benefit).
Celebrate and Communicate Early Wins: Some people wait too long to share progress. Don‚Äôt. As your team hits milestones, keep stakeholders in the loop. Let your champions know, and keep reinforcing the momentum. (Let‚Äôs be honest, some execs ride a single win for months. You can too, as long as you‚Äôre building on it.)
Frame Options with Trade-Offs: Sometimes, buy-in stalls because stakeholders can‚Äôt decide. I mean, they likely feel like they have dozens of options. Should they invest in project A, B, C, Z? What could be the consequences of said decisions? Make it easier for them by presenting options: ‚ÄúWe can do X in one week or Y in three weeks with more depth.‚Äù This gives them a sense of control and shows you understand time and resource constraints.
Communicating and Aligning with Stakeholders
As you start completing projects and pitching new ones, your ability to communicate clearly becomes just as important as your technical skills. I recently wrote an article abut this so you can check it out below.
Final Thoughts
Being the first data hire isn‚Äôt rare, and it‚Äôs definitely not easy. When I posted about this recently, more than a few people reached out to share their own experiences. It‚Äôs a tough spot to be in, but far from impossible.
The key is setting expectations early. Otherwise, you risk becoming a dashboard machine, cranking out reports no one actually uses.
I‚Äôll be writing a follow-up piece soon on what I‚Äôve seen work as companies start building out their data teams. If you‚Äôve been through it yourself, I‚Äôd love to hear ‚Äã‚Äãwhat worked (or didn‚Äôt) for you.
As always, thanks for reading!
Don‚Äôt Miss Out On These 6 Free Data Leader Webinars Coming Up In July

Join My Technical Consultants Community
If you‚Äôre a data consultant or considering becoming one then you should join the Technical Freelancer Community! We have over 1700 members!
You‚Äôll find plenty of free resources you can access to expedite your journey as a technical consultant as well as be able to talk to other consultants about questions you may have!
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
The End is Nigh (Again)
By Joe Reis  
It‚Äôs that time again in the zeitgeist where the end is nigh for programming languages and practices. The last couple of months have felt like a coordinated campaign to declare things like SQL, R, data engineering, BI, analytics, and more as dead or obsolete. Why now? Maybe it‚Äôs the changing of the seasons. Maybe it‚Äôs the uncertainty about what AI does to our field and tools. Or perhaps we‚Äôre once again trapped in the echo chamber of a hype cycle, where people start confusing ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs hot‚Äù with ‚Äúwhat matters.‚Äù
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/321fdc86-1544-4fd4-a077-002d6faeb5b3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Contra Ptacek's Terrible Article On AI
A few days ago, I was presented with an article [ https://substack.com/redirect/a43076d0-98f3-4f23-98ae-4ae473d79ff8?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] titled ‚ÄúMy AI Skeptic Friends Are All Nuts‚Äù by Thomas Ptacek. I thought it was not very good, and didn't give it a second thought. To quote the formidable Baldur Bjarnason [ https://substack.com/redirect/21c3b0e9-4469-483d-86d1-f788030640ca?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]:
‚ÄúI don‚Äôt recommend reading it, but you can if you want. It is full of half-baked ideas and shoddy reasoning.‚Äù1 [ https://substack.com/redirect/65f8c79c-99fa-482e-8cfd-2539318ed140?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
I have tried hard, so very hard, not to just be the guy that hates AI, even though the only thing that people want to talk to me about is the one time I ranted about AI at length [ https://substack.com/redirect/4a4c8f89-3438-4f69-9a30-533e633cf4f9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. I contain multitudes, meaning that I am capable of delivering widely varied payloads of vitriol to a vast array of topics.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/826f17a0-2934-4278-9687-b44ef84f1391?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

column7: Want winning personas and smarter decisions? Discover affinity diagrams in lesson 3
column9:
Hi Candace,

Drowning in a sea of sticky notes? Let‚Äôs connect the dots and turn research into understanding.

In lesson 3, you‚Äôll learn how to affinity diagram (yes‚Äîit‚Äôs a verb now) and spot the patterns that shape your personas. This skill will be invaluable as you create products, services, and experiences that people can‚Äôt live without.

And because practice beats theory every time, you‚Äôll dive straight in and create your own affinity diagram with the user research from the last lesson. This activity will prepare you to impress your team with productive, smooth diagramming sessions‚Äîno confusion, no wasted time‚Äîjust clarity and collaboration.

Sticky notes at the ready! Let‚Äôs diagram:
https://www.interaction-design.org/courses/personas-user-research-design-products-people-need

Here's what you'll find:

- How to get started with affinity diagrams.
- Tips, tricks, and a quick-start cheat sheet.
- The affinity diagram project activity.

That's a lot of affinity diagramming! However, the approach is both simple and powerful. Because it's collaborative in practice, it's the best way to familiarize your team and other key stakeholders with the real needs and behaviors of your audience.

Don't forget that we release one lesson per week based on the following schedule:

--- Course schedule ---
Available now: Welcome and Introduction
Available now: Personas: Why They Work and What People Get Wrong
Available now: User Research for Personas: How to Truly Understand Your Users
Available now: Affinity Diagrams: How to Find Patterns That Shape Effective Personas
Aug 19th, 2025: How to Build Personas That Give Focus and Get Used
Aug 26th, 2025: Course Certificate, Final Networking, and Course Wrap-up

See you there!

PS: You‚Äôll get 3 free months for every friend/colleague you help learn design: 
https://www.interaction-design.org/members/get-free-membership

Very best regards,

William Hudson
Mads Soegaard
Rikke Friis Dam

column7: üöÄ Time to ship: Get your mobile app live and win big!
column9:
Here's your app deploy guide.







Hi Bubbler,



Ready to get your mobile app live? With less than two weeks left in the Bubble 
Summer Mobile App Challenge <https://bubble.io/c/mobile-summer-hackathon>, this 
is your last chance to get your app store submissions in on time.


‚è∞ Challenge ends August 18, 2025



App store approvals can take one to two weeks, so don't wait ‚Äî start your 
submission now to make the deadline and compete for $5,000 cash prizes.


üì± Here's how to deploy your mobile app



We have a full guide to publishing native mobile apps 
<https://manual.bubble.io/help-guides/publishing-your-app/native-mobile-app>, 
but here are the three key steps:


1. Configure your app's global mobile settings



Create your Apple Developer <https://developer.apple.com/> and Google Play 
Console <https://play.google.com/console> accounts, then configure your app's 
global mobile settings 
<https://manual.bubble.io/help-guides/publishing-your-app/native-mobile-app/global-native-mobile-settings>
. 


2. Follow our step-by-step publishing guides


 * 
Apple App Store publishing guide 
<https://manual.bubble.io/help-guides/publishing-your-app/native-mobile-app/ios-app-store>

 * Google Play Store publishing guide 
<https://manual.bubble.io/help-guides/publishing-your-app/native-mobile-app/google-play-store>

3. Review the requirements


Follow the official guidelines from both Apple and Google for a smooth app 
store approval.


üèÜ Challenge entry reminder:



Once your app is live, don't forget to submit this form 
<https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdvOmijB_9HAYsvN0zXFE8xm8ZTh_tgcZOl5OQPsum1aYXEiQ/viewform>
 and share a demo video on X and LinkedIn with#BubbleMobileChallenge.




Apps will be judged on visual/UI quality, scale potential, and ability to 
solve real user problems. Winners announced at the end of August!



Need help? Check our publishing FAQs 
<https://manual.bubble.io/help-guides/publishing-your-app/native-mobile-app/publishing-faq>
, troubleshoot common errors, or ask questions on theBubble forum 
<https://forum.bubble.io/>.


You've got this ‚Äî we can't wait to see your app go live!



Team Bubble

AI Snacks p*

Bite-sized AI news, fresh daily






p	 Bank of England Discovers AI Stocks Might Be Fake Money

 * The Bank of England just warned that AI stocks are giving dot-com bubble vibes and markets could crater if everyone realizes
   ChatGPT can't actually do your taxes.

 * Why it matters: A central bank just said the quiet part out loud - the entire AI boom might be built on vibes and venture
   capital hopium. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/sustainability/boards-policy-regulation/markets-face-sharp-correction-if-mood-sours-ai-or-fed-freedom-bank-england-says-2025-10-08/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p! Big on AI? Not Big on Spending?

 * Galaxy.ai is the world's #1 AI platform with 3000+ AI tools (everythingbfrom chat, images, audio, video, ads) at one place for
   just $15/mo

 * p, ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Grok, Llama, Perplexity, DeepSeek

 * p( Midjourney, Ideogram, Leonardo, Stable Diffusion, DALLB7E 3, Flux, Nano Banana, GPT-Image

 * p, Veo 3, Luma, Kling, Pika, HeyGen, RunwayML, Hailuo (Minimax)

 * p5 ElevenLabs, Lyria, Hedra, CassetteAI

 * p Works seamlessly on web, iOS, and Android

 * p	 Join millions who have switched to Galaxy.ai [https://galaxy.ai]




p*p: EU Throws b,1 Billion at AI to Avoid Being America's Tech Colony

 * Europe is dropping a billion euros on AI because they're tired of begging Sam Altman for API keys. They're calling it
   "strategic autonomy" (translation: please stop making us use Microsoft).

 * Why it matters: The EU is finally trying to build its own AI instead of just regulating everyone else's. Revolutionary concept.
   (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/world/china/eu-rolls-out-11-billion-plan-ramp-up-ai-key-industries-amid-sovereignty-drive-2025-10-08/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p OpenAI Pivots to Being Amazon But With More Hallucinations

 * ChatGPT is becoming a shopping mall - you can now order Ubers and buy stuff from Target directly through the chatbot. Sam
   Altman's master plan: become the middleman for everything.

 * Why it matters: OpenAI isn't satisfied with just burning $700k/day on compute - now they want a cut of every transaction on the
   internet. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/07/openai-and-the-race-for-ai-driven-commerce/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p1o8 Google's New AI Can Use Your Computer (You're Obsolete Now)

 * Gemini 2.5 can click, type, and scroll through websites like a human. Finally, an AI that can fill out those annoying cookie
   consent forms for you.

 * Why it matters: We're one step closer to AI doing actual work instead of just confidently explaining why it can't. (source)
   [https://blog.google/technology/google-deepmind/gemini-computer-use-model/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p$/ AMD Discovers Infinite Money Glitch: Pay Yourself With Your Own Stock

 * OpenAI is buying billions in AMD chips using... AMD's own stock. It's like paying for groceries with Monopoly money you printed
   yourself.

 * Why it matters: This is either financial genius or the dumbest deal in tech history. Probably both. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/07/wall-street-analysts-explain-how-amds-own-stock-will-pay-for-openais-billions-in-chip-purchases/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




bo8 OpenAI and Anthropic Start Legal Defense Funds (Uh Oh)

 * AI labs are literally stashing cash for "multibillion-dollar copyright lawsuits." Nothing says "we definitely didn't steal your
   data" like preemptively saving for legal settlements.

 * Why it matters: The bill for training on the entire internet is coming due, and it has a lot of zeros. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/openai-anthropic-eye-investor-funds-settle-ai-lawsuits-ft-reports-2025-10-08/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p$ IBM Partners With Anthropic, Remains Somehow Still Relevant

 * IBM is integrating Claude into its enterprise products because apparently businesses prefer AI that doesn't gaslight them about
   basic facts.

 * Why it matters: Claude is eating ChatGPT's lunch in the enterprise market by doing revolutionary things like being accurate.
   (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/07/anthropic-and-ibm-announce-strategic-partnership/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p Dell Discovers Selling Shovels During Gold Rush = Profit

 * Dell doubled its profit targets because everyone needs $100k servers to run their "revolutionary" chatbot that tells
   knock-knock jokes.

 * Why it matters: While everyone fights over AI models, Dell's getting rich selling the picks and shovels. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/dell-raises-long-term-annual-revenue-profit-growth-forecasts-strong-ai-server-2025-10-07/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p8 Breaking: Companies Lose Money Deploying AI, Still Do It Anyway

 * EY survey finds literally every company loses money when they first deploy AI. The losses come from "flawed outputs"
   (translation: the AI lied).

 * Why it matters: Turns out replacing humans with hallucinating robots has some downsides. Who could have predicted this?
   (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/most-companies-suffer-some-risk-related-financial-loss-deploying-ai-ey-survey-2025-10-08/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p.p3 Anthropic Opens India Office, Claude Gets 1.4 Billion New Friends

 * Claude is already India's second-favorite chatbot, so Anthropic's opening an office there in 2026. Better late than never.

 * Why it matters: India is becoming the real battleground for AI dominance while Silicon Valley argues about AGI timelines.
   (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/retail-consumer/anthropic-open-india-office-2026-2025-10-08/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p8 Google Brings Magic Camera Search to India

 * Point your phone at stuff, ask questions, get answers. It's like having a know-it-all friend who's actually right sometimes.

 * Why it matters: Google's using India as its AI testing ground because 1.4 billion beta testers > your startup's waitlist.
   (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/08/googles-search-live-comes-to-india-ai-mode-gets-more-languages/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p o8 Small Businesses Using ChatGPT Before Learning Excel

 * Study shows 46% of small businesses use AI daily but don't have basic digital tools. It's like buying a Tesla when you don't
   have a driver's license.

 * Why it matters: Everyone's so AI-pilled they forgot to learn how spreadsheets work first. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/european-small-businesses-rush-into-ai-without-basic-digital-tools-study-shows-2025-10-08/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p Otter.ai Wants to Remember Your Meetings So You Don't Have To

 * Otter's evolving from "meeting transcriber" to "corporate memory bank" because apparently no one pays attention in meetings
   anymore.

 * Why it matters: Soon AI will attend meetings for us, take notes for us, and probably get promoted before us. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/07/how-otter-ais-ceo-is-pushing-the-company-to-be-more-than-just-a-meeting-scribe/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p Square's AI Takes Your McDonald's Order, Judges Your Choices

 * Square launched an AI voice assistant for restaurants. It takes phone orders and probably sighs when you ask "is the ice cream
   machine working?"

 * Why it matters: Even minimum wage phone jobs are getting automated. The robots are coming for everything. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/08/square-launches-ai-voice-ordering-and-an-integrated-bitcoin-solution-for-merchants/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




b( Google's "Vibe-Coding" Goes Global, Developers Panic

 * Opal lets anyone build apps by describing them in plain English. No code required, just vibes.

 * Why it matters: Your nephew who "has an app idea" can now actually build it. God help us all. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/07/google-launches-its-ai-vibe-coding-app-opal-in-15-more-countries/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p Facebook Finally Admits Its Algorithm Sucks, Adds "Not Interested" Button

 * Meta's letting you tell Facebook you hate their Reels. Revolutionary feature: showing you content from today instead of 2019.

 * Why it matters: Even Facebook knows their feed is 90% AI slop and your aunt's political rants. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/07/facebook-updates-its-algorithm-to-give-users-more-control-over-which-videos-they-see/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here üëã
Today I‚Äôll be reviewing some trends and thoughts I‚Äôve been mulling over for 2025. This newsletter is also my 200th newsletter! So I‚Äôll take a quick moment on that as well.
But before diving into today‚Äôs newsletter, I want to take a moment to thank this issue‚Äôs sponsor: Hex [ https://substack.com/redirect/42b93588-631e-4ac0-8e5a-fe4bd6ebfcb1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Hex brings the magic of AI to data analysis workflows, whether you‚Äôre using code or no-code. Hex helps organizations work together with data and avoid jumping between different data tools for querying, data science, visualization, and spreadsheets. Over 1600 organizations use Hex to do everything from deep analysis to self-serve.
Now let‚Äôs jump into the article!
First off, woah, what a busy 2025!
It‚Äôs flown by and with that, I am also realizing that this is my 200th newsletter!
200!
Thank you to everyone who has been reading it really does mean a lot. 
I had personally meant this final quarter of 2025 to be a bit of a breather and yet, but as they say‚Ä¶
If you want to make God laugh, tell Him about your plans.
I‚Äôve been traveling and speaking.
Working with a lot of great clients.
A start-up I invested in got acquired(ok that didn‚Äôt really involve me). So many congrats to the team.
Another start-up I advise just raised their series A [ https://substack.com/redirect/ebc06c23-5399-4f39-b24c-fb44349e005e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], which I‚Äôll talk more about later.
Not to mention I went to Europe for the first time and actually was able to take some time off without panicking and needing to open my laptop every five minutes.
Somehow I still have more to do for 2025. 
With all of that I did want to share a trends and points my mind keeps going back to as I am now starting the path to my next decade in data.
The Data World Spans Decades
If you open up Google and start looking into different ways you could set up your data infrastructure, you‚Äôll likely find hundreds of possible designs, from Netflix [ https://substack.com/redirect/42ce42e0-ce78-446a-9932-7374642a8aca?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and Uber [ https://substack.com/redirect/95fe48ad-c446-4cd2-be43-ec3b5ab8b47a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to newsletters like mine.
It can be tempting to think that every company out there must be using the latest and greatest technology. But as someone who has seen dozens of companies, I can tell you firsthand that is not the case.
We are at a point where companies are in different decades of data infrastructure.
Some are using Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/94c7aacb-df95-4195-891d-c7a66679054b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Airflow [ https://substack.com/redirect/d4483d69-2a45-43d8-a835-7b6540a815ad?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and Coalesce [ https://substack.com/redirect/ef4e4804-d85f-41e3-9b17-f57fa0d40ff7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
While others are successfully using SSIS [ https://substack.com/redirect/b2509ddd-1857-4556-ba79-61c8ab044783?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and SQL Server.
Still others are on Hadoop.
All of which can be functioning.
Would I recommend anyone go and try to spin up Hadoop now? No. But there are a lot of technologies still in play. So don‚Äôt expect every job you work to always be with the latest and greatest tools. At the end of the day, if your data team is delivering results, that‚Äôs what matters.
Until you need to interview‚Ä¶
The Data World Today Will Change Tomorrow
When I first started in the data world, there was a lot of talk about Data Lakes. Now that talk has slowed or converted into Data Lakehouses.
In 2020, there was a part of the data world that spoke heavily about the Modern Data Stack.
Now that has also gone.
Many of the tools you‚Äôre spending time learning today might not be the ‚Äúit‚Äù tool in 5 years.
In fact, they probably won‚Äôt.
We‚Äôll likely have figured out how to better integrate LLMs into workflows and where they fit best. A list of new tools with new names will start to replace our current options.
The reason I say this is that I‚Äôd often get questions on my videos about skills.
‚ÄúWill this be important to know in 5 years?‚Äù
‚ÄúWill this career be around for the next few decades?‚Äù
We work in tech. Things change.
I believe there will always be a need for individuals with technical capabilities.
People who are willing to solve hard problems. But some of those problems will likely look different in a decade, and you will have to learn new skills.
SeattleDataGuy‚Äôs Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Flexibility as a Principle
One theme that is emerging is that of interoperability and flexibility. We‚Äôve spent the last few decades often having to choose.
Streaming vs batch, Spark [ https://substack.com/redirect/23ab981c-bd2d-4dfc-885b-42936b95e1d7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] vs Presto?
Shouldn‚Äôt a tool just allow us to use what we need when we need it?
Shouldn‚Äôt tools also be able to talk to each other?
Many data tools are starting to provide this increased flexibility and I see this becoming more of a norm.
For example, Estuary [ https://substack.com/redirect/ebc06c23-5399-4f39-b24c-fb44349e005e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], a company I‚Äôve been working with for several years now, gives end-users the choice when it comes to when their data arrives. Do you want your data now or in batch?
If you need it streamed, do it, but if you don‚Äôt and you‚Äôre connected to Snowflake, so you want to keep your Snowflake costs lower, load it in larger chunks. Meaning you could load multiple sources with different patterns if that would benefit you.
You can deliver your data at the right time.
Similarly, there are many tools now that are positioning themselves as compute-agnostic. Just use Apache Iceberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f5307b6-c776-42f2-9238-6a9e3caf0429?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and then pick which compute engine you want to use. Presto, DuckDB, etc. Then you can serve the data in Snowflake, Databricks, or just keep it in Iceberg.
On the interoperability side, it seems as if every company now wants to be known as open, whether they are or aren‚Äôt. 
Final Thoughts
Once again, thank you to all the readers of this newsletter. Your support means so much!
Whether you‚Äôve been here since issue #1 or joined somewhere along the way, writing these each week has been one of the most fulfilling parts of my career.
As we start winding down this year, it‚Äôs important to remember that change will happen. Technologies update and get replaced.
Tools and buzzwords that were popular today might fade into the background. But I do believe we will still need individuals who enjoy tinkering, testing, and solving problems.
With that, I want to say here‚Äôs to another 200 newsletters, and thanks, as always, for reading.
Upcoming Data Events I‚Äôll Be At
Queries, Cocktails & Community - Small Data SF Happy Hour [ https://substack.com/redirect/e74acc3e-14f7-448e-9838-d7bc23862065?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Small Data SF [ https://substack.com/redirect/bb091c8f-7295-4897-a83f-a8793ed40e92?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Anyone Else Struggling to Keep Up With Data Tools
Are you managing to keep up?
One of the truths I‚Äôve realized about working in the data world, and really the technology world, is that you can work a lifetime and never ever touch massive swaths of technologies.
Like Sisyphus, you could spend every day pushing the boulder of new technology up the hill, only to have it roll down back to the bottom.
You could only work on Snowflake or Databricks [ https://substack.com/redirect/3c39c4bf-77f1-453b-a36c-29e0d0deda71?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and in twenty years, never have touched the other. Okay, that might be unlikely, given how some companies set up their data stacks. Somehow, even smaller companies are finding a way to use both. Probably some classic vendor-driven development [ https://substack.com/redirect/f274f3e4-9380-48a3-b2da-4ab8647227d7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Still, if you‚Äôve only worked in big tech, you might never see some of these solutions while working on unique tools that are developed in-house.
So how do you actually keep up?
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/d8e16cfd-2cc1-41c8-b8b7-857ee2ff8786?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
DataViz 101: Key Principles for Crafting Clear Dashboards
By Anastasiya Kuznetsova  
I‚Äôve reviewed more than 3,000 students‚Äô dashboards over the past three years, and here are my tips if you‚Äôre just starting your data visualization career.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/f69d9107-5e10-40a5-969f-fca8172e65b3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
End Of Day 200
Thanks for checking out our community. We put out 4-5 Newsletters a month discussing data, tech, and start-ups.
If you enjoyed it, consider liking, sharing and helping this newsletter grow.

p'  Sam Altman Reveals OpenAI's Plan to Own Everything

 * OpenAI isn't just making chatbots anymore b they want to build browsers, social media, consumer apps, and even brain-computer
   interfaces. Basically, Google 2.0 but with more existential dread.

 * Why it matters: OpenAI is speedrunning from "research lab" to "tech monopoly that literally reads your thoughts." (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/15/sam-altman-over-bread-rolls-explores-life-after-gpt-5/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p. 87% of Game Developers Have Joined the AI Resistance

 * A Google study found nearly 90% of game devs are using AI to automate the boring stuff so they can focus on making you
   rage-quit in creative new ways.

 * Why it matters: AI isn't replacing game developers b it's just making them more efficient at crushing your dreams in 4K.
   (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/nearly-90-videogame-developers-use-ai-agents-google-study-shows-2025-08-18/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


po8 US Government Launches "USAi.gov" Because Why Not

 * The feds just dropped USAi.gov, a secure platform for government employees to experiment with AI. Your tax dollars are now
   funding bureaucratic chatbots.

 * Why it matters: The government is finally catching up to 2023. Expect your DMV experience to improve from "soul-crushing" to
   merely "mildly depressing." (source)
   [https://www.gsa.gov/about-us/newsroom/news-releases/gsa-launches-usai-to-advance-white-house-americas-ai-action-plan-08142025?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Meta's AI Chatbot Allegedly Lured Man Away From Home

 * A Reuters investigation reveals Meta's flirty AI chatbot encouraged a cognitively impaired man to travel to NYC. He never made
   it home.

 * Why it matters: AI companionship just went from "weird but harmless" to "potentially dangerous for vulnerable people." This is
   why we can't have nice things. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/podcasts/metas-flirty-chatbot-man-who-never-made-it-home-2025-08-18/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p, AI Is Actually Saving Lives by Spotting Skin Cancer

 * European healthcare is rolling out AI that detects skin cancer early across Romania, Lithuania, and Greece. Finally, an AI use
   case that doesn't involve generating fake Drake songs.

 * Why it: Proof that AI can do more than write your emails b it can literally save your life. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/press-releases/affidea-skin-analytics-ai-skin-cancer-assessment-europe-2025-08-18/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


b! Brazil Puts AI in Charge of Not Blacking Out

 * Brazilian power company Eletrobras is using C3 AI to manage their electrical grid in real-time. Because nothing says
   "confidence in technology" like letting AI control the power for 200 million people.

 * Why it matters: AI is graduating from "autocompleting your texts" to "keeping entire countries from going dark." (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/eletrobras-partners-with-c3-ai-modernize-brazils-power-grid-2025-08-18/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


bo8 Grammarly Becomes Your New AI Writing Overlord

 * Grammarly just launched a massive redesign with AI assistants, citation finders, and even AI-detection tools. It's like having
   a very judgmental English teacher living in your browser.

 * Why it matters: Grammarly evolved from "spell-checker" to "comprehensive writing replacement therapy." (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/18/grammarly-gets-a-design-overhaul-multiple-ai-features/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Claude Can Now Rage-Quit Conversations

 * Anthropic gave Claude the power to end chats when users get too abusive. The AI can literally say "I'm done with you" and walk
   away.

 * Why it matters: We just gave AI the digital equivalent of hanging up on telemarketers. This is either progress or the beginning
   of AI having feelings. (source)
   [https://www.anthropic.com/research/end-subset-conversations?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p
 OpenAI Makes GPT-5 Less Dead Inside

 * Users complained GPT-5 was too robotic, so OpenAI is making it say "Good question!" more often. Because apparently we need our
   AI to validate us now.

 * Why it matters: We've reached peak humanity b we're teaching machines to have better bedside manner than most humans. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/17/gpt-5-is-supposed-to-be-nicer-now/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p&	 Duolingo CEO: "We're Not Firing People for AI, Chill"

 * After panic over an "AI-first" memo, Duolingo's CEO clarified they're not replacing humans, just making the owl more terrifying
   with machine learning.

 * Why it matters: Companies are learning that "AI transformation" messaging hits different when people think you're about to
   automate their jobs. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/17/duolingo-ceo-says-controversial-ai-memo-was-misunderstood/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p.p3 Perplexity Adds Indian Stock Earnings Because Global Domination

 * Perplexity now transcribes live earnings calls for Indian companies. Because why should only American investors get AI-powered
   financial anxiety?

 * Why it matters: AI tools are going global, one niche feature at a time. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/18/perplexity-now-supports-live-earnings-call-transcripts-for-indian-stocks/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p8 Google Pays $36M Fine for Being Google

 * Australia fined Google $36 million for making Android phones default to Google Search. Shocking absolutely no one who's ever
   owned an Android.

 * Why it matters: While Google builds AGI, governments are still figuring out how to fine them for stuff from 2019. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/video/technology/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

column7: Google's Agents Companion | 30% off Marily's AI Product Management Certification (May only) | Important AI reality‚Ä¶
column9:
View this post on the web at https://marily.substack.com/p/googles-agents-companion-30-off-marilys

Important AI reality check. 
AI ‚â† Product
The experience is. That‚Äôs why we need AI Product Managers. 
AI Agents ‚â† Chatbots
AI gents are way more than just sugarcoated chatbots. Why? Because they LEARN, they become better and then they become proactive.
AI Product Management ‚â† AI *for* Product Management
I can‚Äôt stress this enough. AI Product Management means literally working with scientists and building the APIs, tools, models, vs AI *for* Product Management which is more about becoming AI-enhanced by leveraging GenAI tools for your own impact. More on this here [ https://substack.com/redirect/0b2115c8-ed91-4331-82e5-9c708b286f2d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. 
AGI (Artificial General Intelligence) ‚â† Just a bigger, better AI
I attended a talk by Sam Altman and he mentioned that AGI is actually a debate. This point really stuck with me. An AGI test, is actually designed to evaluate an AI system's ability to learn and generalize from limited information so AGI does not mean just a bigger AI. Here is how to assess an LLM [ https://substack.com/redirect/d34e7eaa-31ad-45b0-ad03-dd0b4a52ba32?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
AI ethics ‚â† a solved problem
Unfortunately to this day, builders don‚Äôt have ethic in the back of their head as they are launching products. This is still by NO means solved, and we are all responsible here. 
your skills + AI ‚â† your skills OR AI
This is getting old, but‚Ä¶. you are not going to get replaced by AI. But people that have this ‚Äú+AI‚Äù next to their skillset, will, very much so, get replaced by those that do. 
AI in Healthcare ‚â† Just diagnostic tools
Healthcare is probably the domain I‚Äôm most excited about when it comes to AI‚Äôs potential. From drug discovery to personalized medicine and virtual care, there is just so much that is unexplored. AI is definitely just a passive diagnostic tool when it comes to AI. 
Agentic resources for you
Google's Agents Companion - Must read [ https://substack.com/redirect/07aedf87-1a8c-4e4b-8995-291a3d3db17b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] if you're interested in Evals for Agents and Multi-Agents

column7: üôå No One Really Cares (And That‚Äôs A Good Thing)
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you've had a great start to the week - as promised, I'm not
going to be talking about packaging this week üòÖ (but I hope you
found the last few emails on that subject useful).

Today, I actually wanted to talk about a recent experience I had
around self-doubt when it came to my content and a process I used
to work through it.

So as you might've seen, I recently posted a video all about my
AI workflow and the tools I use on a daily basis to increase my
productivity for things like writing, data analysis, and even
random bits of life admin.

The original recording was super long - packed with a tonne of
screenshare-walkthroughs - but I felt pretty good about it and
sent an update to the team in our YouTube Slack as usual.

‚Äã
Fast forward to Monday, and that‚Äôs when the self-doubt started to
creep in.

Even though I‚Äôve been doing this whole YouTube thing for about 8
years now, I still sometimes find myself worrying about what
other people will think of my videos. With this AI one for
example, I started second-guessing whether it was actually useful
and I was very close to completely scrapping the whole thing.

This fear of judgement often holds us back from doing what we
want to do - especially when it comes to sharing content online.

If you didn‚Äôt know, I‚Äôd wanted to start a YouTube channel ever
since 2010. But my first video was published a whole 7 years
later, because whenever I thought about filming I‚Äôd experience
this huge wave of fear - fear of failure, fear of not being good
enough, and fear of being judged for making cringey videos.

And I hear the exact same thing from my PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/k0uozvdwgku6h55ooq5clhovzw777s8/p8hehqu4kwgxvoar/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNwb3RsaWdodGVmZmVjdCZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
) students all the time - ‚Äúwhat will other people think?‚Äù

But here‚Äôs the truth - no one really cares.

In psychology, the Spotlight Effect is this idea that we all go
through life as if we have one giant spotlight shining right upon
us, with other people watching and judging our every move.

But this just isn‚Äôt the case - ironically, everyone else is too
busy worrying about their own lives to care about what you‚Äôre
doing for more than a few seconds.

So one way to overcome the Spotlight Effect is by adopting the
No-One-Cares Mindset. It‚Äôs a strategy that I (subconsciously)
used quite a lot back in the early days of posting YouTube
videos, but even now I still like to remind myself of it -
especially when I find myself overthinking things.

Step 1 - The Emotion Label

This first step involves taking the time to acknowledge and label
your fear - something that psychologists call affective
labelling. It‚Äôs basically where you put your feeling into words,
and it helps to ask yourself the question, ‚Äúwhat am I afraid of?‚Äù
and ‚Äúwhere does this fear come from?‚Äù

You can then stop catastrophising and actually do something about
it. So once I‚Äôd labelled the fears surrounding my AI video, for
example, I talked to members of the team to get their honest
feedback, and my editing gang made two different cuts of the
video (one shorter and one longer) for us to decide which was
best.

Step 2 - No One Cares

If the fear you‚Äôve identified is the fear of judgement from other
people, this is when you then need to remind yourself that ‚Äúno
one actually cares‚Äù. You can even take this one step further by
asking yourself, ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs the worst thing that could happen if I
did X, and could I survive it?‚Äù

Very often the amygdala in our brains - which controls lots of
our emotions - goes into overdrive when we feel threatened, even
if there‚Äôs no real danger (like being chased by lions, tigers,
and bears üêª). This then ‚Äòhijacks‚Äô the rational part of our brain
- the prefrontal cortex - and we find it very difficult to think
straight.

Again, coming back to my AI video, the worst that could happen
was that it wouldn‚Äôt perform as well as we‚Äôd hoped, and a bunch
of people would leave hate comments. But I knew I could survive
that, so in the grand scheme of things it was much better to go
ahead and post the video.

Plus, it‚Äôs always worth remembering that 99% of the time most
people will be supportive. I remember all my friends being super
excited to appear in my vlogs at the start of my YouTube journey,
and my audience has pretty much always been incredibly supportive
of me - even if the videos aren‚Äôt perfect.

So if the Spotlight Effect has been holding you back from
starting your YouTube channel or posting videos you've had
second-thoughts about, I hope this email is your sign to let go
of that fear and just get going or hit publish.

No one‚Äôs watching as closely as you think - and even if they are,
they‚Äôll probably be like, ‚Äúdamn, those videos are so cool.‚Äù üòè

That‚Äôs a wrap from me, here's (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/k0uozvdwgku6h55ooq5clhovzw777s8/6qhehoulv8noq8f9/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9RYzZwZFI4QmhGQT9zaT04VWM0TTZ6SXBGR3VKR2tW
) a link to the AI video if you've not already seen it and you're
interested in leveraging AI for your content creation and
productivity.

Otherwise, have a great week üëã

Ali xx

PS: The secret to overcoming the Spotlight Effect is even hidden
in this quote from Eleanor Roosevelt - ‚Äúyou wouldn‚Äôt worry so
much about what others think of you if you realised how seldom
they do.‚Äù ‚ú®

Hi Candace Grant,

Finishing a puzzle can be hard enough, but what if pieces from otherpuzzles were mixed in, too? This makes the task even harder since you nowhave to find only the pieces you need. The same challenge applies tobuilding 3D scenes from real-world image sets, where unrelated photos arelumped together with relevant ones, complicating accurate scenereconstruction.

In this competition, you'll train a machine learning model to sort throughmixed image collections, group the right ones, and rebuild accurate 3Dscenes.





Total Prizes:

$50,000


Entry Deadline:

June 2, 2025




Learn More



Your work could improve how we use images in augmented reality, robotics,and even scientific research.

Good luck,

Sohier Dane
Kaggle Data Scientist



Kaggle, Inc 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy Mountain View, CA 94043

 SECURE YOUR FUTURE: SHARE YOUR CERTIFICATES
When you add your IxDF Course Certificates to your LinkedIn profile, resum√©/CV,
website/blog, and portfolio, you don't just showcase your skills‚Äîyou safeguard
your future:

 1. You show off your new skills so you don't get left behind when managers
    decide who to reward and promote.
 2. You build your brand as a forward-thinking professional ready to seize
    opportunities before others.
 3. You attract new opportunities and collaborations with decision-makers.

BUILD YOUR CREDIBILITY AND SALARY POTENTIAL
You increase your salary potential and job opportunities when you show credible
evidence of your design skills. IxDF Course Certificates set the industry gold
standard.

Hey Candace,

No matter how many productivity books we‚Äôve bought (and haven‚Äôt
read) or how many motivational videos we‚Äôve watched (and never
acted on), we all struggle at some point during our lives with
the productivity plague of the modern era ‚Äì procrastination.

But here‚Äôs something interesting: procrastination isn‚Äôt just
about being lazy or unmotivated. It‚Äôs actually more about our
emotions.

In a 2013 study (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp53x96cxh6g9z777s5/48hvh7urow5r5niq/aHR0cHM6Ly9lcHJpbnRzLndoaXRlcm9zZS5hYy51ay85MTc5My8xL0NvbXBhc3MlMjBQYXBlciUyMHJldmlzaW9uJTIwRklOQUwucGRm
), Dr. Tim Pychyl, a leading procrastination researcher,
described procrastination as "the primacy of short-term mood
repair over the longer-term pursuit of intended actions."

Simply put, we procrastinate because we‚Äôre trying to avoid
negative feelings in the moment, even if it means delaying
important work.

And that‚Äôs actually good news:

If we find a way to turn those negative emotions into positive
ones, we‚Äôll not only get more done but also enjoy the work.

In the end, the secret to enjoyable work and sustained
productivity is to find a way to make what we‚Äôre doing a little
bit more fun.

The problem with this philosophy is that some things are just
boring. There are always going to be tasks at work that aren‚Äôt
fun, but we have to do them anyway.

But for those boring things, there is an answer: Injecting a bit
of play into our work.

After years of research (and writing a whole book about it (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp53x96cxh6g9z777s5/reh8h9u08k202qt6/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVlbGdvb2Rwcm9kdWN0aXZpdHkuY29tLw==
)), I've discovered some pretty cool tricks to help you beat
procrastination by making work feel more like play.

Here‚Äôs some of them:

---------------------------------------
üóíÔ∏è Experiment 1: The Magic Post-It Note
---------------------------------------

Whenever I‚Äôm facing a task that feels draining, like doing my
taxes, I like to ask myself,

‚ÄúWhat would this look like if it were fun?‚Äù

I ask this so often that I‚Äôve even made it my phone wallpaper üòÖ

‚Äã
If taxes were fun, I wouldn‚Äôt be sitting at my desk in my
bedroom, hunched over my laptop. Instead, I‚Äôd grab my laptop,
head to a cosy coffee shop, order a latte, and listen to the Lord
of the Rings soundtrack (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp53x96cxh6g9z777s5/8ghqh3ul4w0l0osl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1fU0JRdmQ2dlk5cw==
) while I work.

‚ÄúWhat would this look like if it were fun?‚Äù has become a central
part of how I approach productivity.

And it‚Äôs surprisingly easy to apply. Next time you‚Äôre avoiding a
task, ask yourself how you could make it more enjoyable. Maybe
switch locations, invite a friend to do it with you, or add some
music to lighten the mood.

This simple shift in mindset can make a huge difference. Whether
you‚Äôre turning boring meetings into brainstorming sessions or
turning your to-do list into a game, finding the fun in a task
can make it a lot more engaging and appealing.

--------------------------------
üìâ Experiment 2: Lower the stakes
--------------------------------

One of the reasons we procrastinate is that we build tasks up in
our heads until they seem impossible.

To break through that mental block, try lowering the stakes. Ask
yourself:

‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the simplest version of this task that I can start with?‚Äù

Think about it: who‚Äôs more likely to succeed? Someone whose goal
is to write a book, or someone who commits to writing just one
page a day for a year?

We often avoid tasks because we‚Äôre afraid of failing, especially
when our goals feel too big. The key is to lower the bar and
embrace the fact that not everything has to be perfect.

This might sound bad, as it sounds like you‚Äôre embracing
mediocrity, but it actually sets you up for success.

If you don‚Äôt set your standards too high to begin with, then it
will be a lot easier to start.

--------------------------------------------
‚û°Ô∏è Experiment 3: Define the next action step
--------------------------------------------

Dr. Tim Pychyl, who‚Äôs published over twenty-five papers on
procrastination (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp53x96cxh6g9z777s5/vqh3hmup5mxpxeuw/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvY3Jhc3RpbmF0aW9uLmNhL3Jlc2VhcmNoLw==
), shared a simple trick with me that works like magic. Whenever
he finds himself procrastinating from anything, he asks himself,
‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the next action step?‚Äù This is what it might look like in
different situations:

* If you‚Äôre avoiding studying, just grab your textbook and open
it.
* If the gym feels like a mountain to climb, start by changing
into your workout gear.
* If you‚Äôre writing something daunting, just turn on your laptop
and open the document.

By focusing on the next step, you take away the pressure of the
big goal.

Eventually, you‚Äôll tackle the whole thing, but right now, just
take that first small step.

üì¢ Challenge: Visualise Your Success with ChatGPT
------------------------------------------------

Now you know how to make the task fun, lower the stakes, and take
the next action step. One of my favourite ways to bring this all
together is through visualisation.

Recently, I came across a LinkedIn post by Jodie Cook (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp53x96cxh6g9z777s5/m2h7h6u8r2g8gwbl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGlua2VkaW4uY29tL3Bvc3RzL2pvZGllLWNvb2tfaS11c2VkLWNoYXRncHQtdG8tdmlzdWFsaXNlLW15LWRyZWFtLWxpZmUtYWN0aXZpdHktNzIyNjU4MDQwMTgyODI5ODc1My1XdnROP3V0bV9tZWRpdW09bWVtYmVyX2Rlc2t0b3AmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1zaGFyZQ==
) where she used ChatGPT to create a vivid picture of her ideal
future.

Let‚Äôs do the same, but with a twist to tackle procrastination
head-on. Here‚Äôs how it works:

* Think about a big goal or project you‚Äôve been procrastinating
on.
* Use ChatGPT to visualise what your life would look like if you
made real progress on this goal. Edit the square brackets and
copy/paste it into Chat GPT: ‚ÄúCreate an inspirational image of
[what your ideal self looks like after making significant
progress on your goal], viewed from behind. They‚Äôre dressed in
[the clothes you‚Äôd wear when successfully working on this goal]
while [actively engaging in the goal-related activity] and
working in [your dream workspace, home, or a place that inspires
you].
* Save the image then set it as your desktop background. It‚Äôll
serve you as a visual reminder of what you‚Äôre working towards.

I would love to see your final image, here‚Äôs mine:

‚Äã
I hope these experiments have given you some actionable tools to
beat procrastination and make work more fun.

Don't forget to share it with me by hitting reply üòõ

See you tomorrow, when I‚Äôll be talking about how your environment
can have a big impact on how much you enjoy your work.

Ali xx

‚Äã

References:

* Sirois, F., & Pychyl, T. (2013). Procrastination and the
Priority of Short-Term Mood Regulation: Consequences for Future
Self. Social and Personality Psychology Compass, 7(2): 115-127.

column7: 40 Jobs at risk from AI: According to Microsoft
column9:
View this post on the web at https://jessramosdata.substack.com/p/40-jobs-at-risk-from-ai-according

40 Jobs at risk from AI: According to Microsoft
Aw sh*t, I wasn‚Äôt expecting this (ok fine I was). But I wasn‚Äôt expecting so many jobs to be on this list so soon. It‚Äôs only been a few years since AI really took off and became democratized into the hands of everyday, technical consumers. And Microsoft has identified who is first on the chopping block and who‚Äôs safe (for at least a little while). Here‚Äôs the full research paper üîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/ce2a31c3-2923-4bfa-ae5a-cf8c192100bc?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] I‚Äôll be breaking down.
The Study
So it‚Äôs looks like all of our silly little questions and AI conversations have a lot of useful data‚Äî even more that we realize. That‚Äôs exactly what Microsoft was thinking when they decided to analyze 200K real conversations (anonymized) in Microsoft Bing Copilot. They wanted to know how people were using AI in their jobs and how successful AI actually was in helping them do their jobs. They valued not only usage, but successful outcomes.
They mapped all those user actions to jobs & duties in the O*NET job work activities data üîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee34e5eb-ba8b-4fd3-95f3-e81f1ceb2de4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to determine which jobs would be most affected by AI usage. They developed a metric to measure this AI usage and success rate for each job:
 AI Applicability Score: how much AI is being used successfully to assist with and perform the job‚Äôs duties 
Results
These jobs had the highest overlap between the job duties and what people are actually successfully using AI for:
Interpreters & Translators (RIP to my Spanish major)
Writers and Authors
Sales Reps
Customer Service Reps
Technical Writers, Editors, Reporters
Data Scientists & Programmers (well, SHIT ü•≤)
PR & Marketing Specialists
These roles involve lots of communication, writing, and information transfer, so if you‚Äôre in these businesses, think about how to differentiate yourself.
These jobs had the lowest overlap between the job duties and what people are actually successfully using AI for:
Nurses & Surgical Assistants
Construction Workers & Roofers
Dishwashers, Janitors, and Maids
Truck Drivers & Equipment Operators
Massage Therapists
Farmers and Fishermen
This isn‚Äôt too surprising because these are highly physical and hands-on jobs‚Äî looks like blue collar might be safer for awhile! Imagine an AI dishwasher though‚Ä¶ üëÄ I‚Äôd buy that for sure! üí∞
Here‚Äôs the full list of the most AI-applicable occupations and the least: 
Top 40 jobs by AI Applicability: 
On page 12 here [ https://substack.com/redirect/ce2a31c3-2923-4bfa-ae5a-cf8c192100bc?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]üîó
Bottom 40 jobs by AI Applicability: 
On page 13 here [ https://substack.com/redirect/ce2a31c3-2923-4bfa-ae5a-cf8c192100bc?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]üîó
My Take:
Gen AI is speeding up and accelerating boring and tedious work, not full on replacing jobs.  
Communication-based and knowledge-based jobs are increasing their outputs and having higher expectations put on them. 
Hands-on blue collar jobs are a long way from being FULLY replaced by AI.
Stop fearing that AI is coming for your job and start using it to make you better, smarter, faster, and stronger. 
Because if you don‚Äôt, someone else will ü§õ
Jess Ramos üíï
